the trick is to use @sharedRoute in the old and new operations and to rename and remove the old operation in the new version.

it is because it is used in an update method where you have `@patch(#{implicitOptionality: true})` probably and this adds a required property nested(`ExternalKey.id`) which then require the need to create new models where everything is optional.
if you stop using @patch(#{implicitOptionality: true}) it will stop creating the model for you and its up to you to describe the accurate patch model.
It is generally preferred that you use `#{implictOptionality: false}`  because this ensures the patch model is correctly defined for use in SDKs (although, admittedly, sdk emitters tend to construct their own patch request models anyway).  There are some templates that allow transforming your types for patch [as in this playground](https://azure.github.io/typespec-azure/playground/?options=%7B%22linterRuleSet%22%3A%7B%22extends%22%3A%5B%22%40azure-tools%2Ftypespec-azure-rulesets%2Fresource-manager%22%5D%7D%7D&%2BQAoWVudW3oARNzIHsKICDELjIwMjEtMTAtMDEtcHJldmlld8g1xDQgIOQA10NvbW1vblTkAY%2FHQCj1ATcuyykuyGoudjUpCiAgYNJpYCwKfeYAs0HoALXrAM4g6AHw5ACIbW9kZWwgRW1wbG95ZWUgaXMgVHJhY2tlZOgAgjzIHFByb3BlcnRpZXM%2B5QDkLi7pAKbkAZZQYXJhbWV0ZXLJMT476ACGyV9wyUTSfMpg6QFDQWdlIG9mIGXIP%2BUBOGFnZT86IGludDMyOwrHKUNpdHnSKmNpdHk%%2FaTHVwZGF0xE%2FFQ1XHDjogIsgLyjvpBGXpAMTmANxk5wGiU3VjY2VlZOUAxckM0z%2FFNuQBTWZhaWzJPkbFDTogIsYJ3Dh3YXMgY2FuY2XKPkPHD%2BQEvccL%2FwFAIGRlbGXpAYBExA3mAPnICyLpA%2F3pA3dtb3bqAcrpA3lNb3ZlUscV6ANyxHNtb3bEaGZyb20gbG9j5gC8xW7EE%2FEDUMszdG%2FPMXRvyi%2F3AJVzcG9uc%2BsEi%2BYAlscW7ACX7gNsxT7FZMZ85gLuzW5hbGlhcyBQYXRjaE3EWzwKICBUIGV4dGVuZHMge30sCiAga2V5c8kTxjwgPSAiIgo%2BID0gT3DkAMphbOoEmjzlAl5lYWJs6wSvPE9taXREZWZhdWx0xg3LHMR0yGkKPj4%2BPjsK8AT45AChyjLkAenrALTzBX7WQtc4LCAi5AbkIiB8ICLqBX4i5gXD5AFbcnAt5AgLaWZpY%2B8Fn%2BUEnscQPzr4ALDlAWtpbnRlcmbkB0dP6AT%2F6gFX9gbSyyl7fQrlB%2BXII8oby1nIf%2BYGHmdldOQA8UHKNeQFUuwGeyDnA%2BZPcuYBtM8vQ8cdUmVwbGFjZUFzeW5jzj%2FlBGLIN0N1c3RvbeUA%2B1PMKizuARfFOeYDoc9w5QOeZVdpdGhvdXRPa9NwbGlzdEJ5yDBHcm91cM9ETMUiUGFyZW501DxTdWJzY3Jp5QK2xzvGM8wZzDnoB2cgc2FtcGzrBG1hY8VEdGhhdOYDaukHKnRvIGRpZmZl5ACE7wPtxSnuALJBxUjvATLrBHjIDeYD7%2FMAkkhFQUTqB1PEfmNoZWNr6gCqZXhpc3RlbuYIzSDGHkXJFO8B9M0d7gio&e=%40azure-tools%2Ftypespec-autorest&vs=%7B%7D):
```
alias PatchModel<
  T extends {},
  keys extends string = ""
> = OptionalProperties<UpdateableProperties<OmitDefaults<OmitProperties<
  T,
  keys
>>>>;

model EmployeePatchProperties is PatchModel<EmployeeProperties>;

model EmployeePatch is PatchModel<Employee, "name" | "properties"> {
  /** rp-specific properties */
  properties?: EmployeePatchProperties;
}
```

In TypeSpec, when defining a multipart request using @multipartBody (not @multipartData), the contentType header is required to explicitly specify the intended multipart type (e.g., "multipart/form-data" or "multipart/mixed").
This requirement is based on the TypeSpec HTTP library documentation, which states:
```
To define a multipart request in HTTP you must set the contentType header to "multipart/form-data" or "multipart/mixed" as described in the content types doc and add a multipart body property decorated with @multipartBody.
```
The reason for this explicit requirement is that TypeSpec supports both "multipart/form-data" and "multipart/mixed". Without the contentType header, the emitter cannot reliably infer which multipart type you intend, as both are valid and have different semantics:
"multipart/form-data" is used for form uploads (e.g., files and fields)
"multipart/mixed" is used for generic multipart payloads, often without named parts
Therefore, the emitter does NOT assume "multipart/form-data" by default if the contentType header is omitted. You must always specify the contentType header for multipart operations to ensure correct OpenAPI generation and Azure guideline compliance.
If you omit the contentType header, your TypeSpec will be considered incomplete and may fail validation or generate ambiguous OpenAPI. This is especially important for Azure services, which must strictly follow the Azure REST API guidelines.
Example (correct):
```
op upload(
  @header contentType: "multipart/form-data",
  @multipartBody body: {
    file: HttpPart<File>;
    metadata: HttpPart<string>;
  },
): void;
```
Summary:
The contentType header is required for multipart operations in TypeSpec.
The emitter cannot assume "multipart/form-data" if contentType is missing.
Always specify the contentType header to comply with Azure guidelines and ensure correct OpenAPI output.

There is no special "tags + identity" PATCH template; the Azure guidance is to move from ArmTagsPatchSync to a custom PATCH model using ArmCustomPatch* and explicitly include identity (and tags) in that model.
Concretely for your SovereignView resource:
1.Keep ManagedServiceIdentityProperty on the resource model (as you already did):
```
model SovereignViewResource is TrackedResource<SovereignViewProperties> {
  ...ResourceNameParameter<SovereignViewResource>;
  ...ManagedServiceIdentityProperty; // adds identity?: ManagedServiceIdentity
}
```
2.Define a PATCH model that includes both tags and identity, and no other mutable properties (since your properties are immutable):
```
/** PATCH body for SovereignView */
model SovereignViewUpdate {
  // tags-only support
  ...Azure.ResourceManager.Foundations.ArmTagsProperty;

  // MSI support – must mirror the envelope identity property
  ...Azure.ResourceManager.ManagedServiceIdentityProperty;
}
```
3.Change your update operation from ArmTagsPatchSync to ArmCustomPatchSync using that model:
```
@armResourceOperations
interface SovereignViews {
  get is ArmResourceRead<SovereignViewResource>;

  // previously: update is ArmTagsPatchSync<SovereignViewResource>;
  update is ArmCustomPatchSync<SovereignViewResource, SovereignViewUpdate>;
}
```
This will:
Satisfy PatchIdentityProperty and the patch-envelope rule by having identity in the PATCH body.
Still keep all RP-specific properties effectively immutable (you simply don’t expose them in the PATCH model).
Align with the recommended ARM practice of using ArmCustomPatch* for PATCH, especially once you have more than tags in the envelope.
